    <article role="article">
      
        
        <header class="page-header">
          
          
            <h1 class="entry-title">
              Starting a Django Project
              
            </h1>
          
        </header>
        
      

      <div class="entry-content">
        <div class="subheading">
  <p class="lead emotional">Answering the question, &#8220;How do I setup a Django (1.5, 1.6, 1.7, or 1.8) Project from scratch?&#8221;</p>
</div>




<p class="center-text">
  <img src="/learn/start-django/img/django-logo-positive.png" style="max-width: 50%;" class="no-border" alt="Official Django logo. Trademark Django Software Foundation.">
</p>




<p><em><a href="http://djangoproject.com">Django</a> is a high-level Python Web framework that encourages rapid development and clean, pragmatic design.</em></p>




<hr>


<p><strong>Welcome!</strong></p>

<ol>
<li><strong>Read over the Introduction and Setup sections.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Then choose your poison &ndash; Django 1.5, 1.6, 1.7, 1.8 &ndash; to setup a Django Project.</strong></li>
<li><strong>After the initial Project setup, move down to the Create an App section to setup a nice and easy app.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Then checkout the summary workflow for a quick-start guide to a Django Project.</strong></li>
</ol>


<p><strong>Cheers!</strong></p>

<blockquote><p>Update: We&rsquo;ve pointed the domain <strong><a href="http://realdjango.com">realdjango.com</a></strong> to this post.</p></blockquote>

<a name="Introduction"></a>
<h2>Introduction</h2>

<p>This tutorial answers the question, <em>&ldquo;How do I setup a Django Project from scratch?&rdquo;</em>. Since you&rsquo;re reading this, I assume (err, hope) you know that Django is a Python web framework built for rapid web development. We&rsquo;ll go through the setup, detailing the basic installation procedures of Django and the dependencies required as well as a few additional libraries/extensions to get you started developing ASAP.</p>

<p>We&rsquo;ll also look at a basic workflow you can use as soon as your project structure is setup.</p>

<p>Finally, be sure to check out the following videos:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://youtu.be/D0MoGRZRtcA">Setting up a Django Project &ndash; part 1 (setup)</a></li>
<li><a href="http://youtu.be/EuOJRop5aBE">Setting up a Django Project &ndash; part 2 (creating an app)</a></li>
</ul>


<blockquote><p>Although these videos are specific to Django 1.5, they&rsquo;ll help you understand the basic workflow for Django 1.6, 1.7, and 1.8 as well.</p></blockquote>

<a name="Tutorial.Requirements"></a>
<h3>Tutorial Requirements</h3>

<p>You should have some Python experience and know basic Unix bash commands. If you&rsquo;ve never used the command line before, please familiarize yourself with the following commands: <em>pwd</em>, <em>cd</em>, <em>ls</em>, <em>rm</em>, and <em>mkdir</em>.</p>

<p>For simplicity, all examples use the Unix-style prompt:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py runserver
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>(The dollar sign is not part of the command.)</p>

<p>Windows equivalent:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>C:<span class="se">\&gt;</span> python manage.py runserver
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Setup"></a>
<h2>Setup</h2>

<p><strong>What you need for a basic dev environment:</strong></p>

<ol>
<li>Python 2.7.x or 3.4.x</li>
<li>easy_install and Pip</li>
<li>Git</li>
<li>virtualenv</li>
<li>Django</li>
<li>Database (SQLite, MySQL, PostgreSQL, MongoDB, etc.)</li>
<li>South (for Django versions prior to 1.7)</li>
<li>Text editor (Sublime, vim, Komodo, gedit)</li>
</ol>


<blockquote><p><strong>Note</strong>: This tutorial utilizes Python version 2.7.8.</p></blockquote>

<a name="Python"></a>
<h3>Python</h3>

<p>Unix environments come pre-installed with Python. To check your Python version, run the command:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python -V
</span><span class='line'>Python 2.7.8
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python3 -V
</span><span class='line'>Python 3.4.2
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>If you already have a 2.7.x version, move on to the next step. If not, <a href="http://python.org/download/">download</a> and install the latest 2.7.x version specific to your operating system.</p>

<a name="easy_install.and.pip"></a>
<h3>easy_install and pip</h3>

<p>Both easy_install and pip are Python Package Managers, which make it <em>much</em> easier to install and upgrade Python packages (and package dependencies).</p>

<p>To download easy_install, go to the <a href="https://pypi.python.org/pypi/setuptools">Python Package Index</a> (PyPI). You need to download setuptools, which includes easy_install. Download the package egg (.egg), then install it directly from the file.</p>

<p>Pip, meanwhile, is a wrapper that relies on easy_install, so you must have easy_install setup and working first before you can install pip. Once easy_install is setup, run the following command to install pip:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>easy_install pip
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Git"></a>
<h3>Git</h3>

<p>For <a href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/Getting-Started-About-Version-Control">version control</a>, we&rsquo;ll be using git. You can check your current version, if you have git already installed, with the following command:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git --version
</span><span class='line'>git version 2.3.0
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>If you do not have a version greater than 1.7.x installed, please <a href="http://git-scm.com/download">download</a> the latest version.</p>

<a name="MySQL"></a>
<h3>MySQL</h3>

<p>SQLite comes pre-installed with Python, and most tutorials utilize SQLite &ndash; so let&rsquo;s push ourselves a bit and use MySQL instead.</p>

<p>First, install MySQL from <a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/installing.html">here</a>.</p>

<p>Next, start the server, and then setup a new database and a user:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
<span class='line-number'>12</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>mysql.server start
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>mysql -u root -p
</span><span class='line'>Enter password:
</span><span class='line'>Welcome to the MySQL monitor.  Commands end with <span class="p">;</span> or <span class="se">\g</span>.
</span><span class='line'>Your MySQL connection id is 1
</span><span class='line'>Type <span class="s1">&#39;help;&#39;</span> or <span class="s1">&#39;\h&#39;</span> <span class="k">for </span>help. Type <span class="s1">&#39;\c&#39;</span> to clear the buffer.
</span><span class='line'>mysql&gt;
</span><span class='line'>mysql&gt; CREATE DATABASE django_db<span class="p">;</span>
</span><span class='line'>Query OK, 1 row affected <span class="o">(</span>0.01 sec<span class="o">)</span>
</span><span class='line'>mysql&gt;
</span><span class='line'>mysql&gt; quit
</span><span class='line'>Bye
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="virtualenv"></a>
<h3>virtualenv</h3>

<p>It&rsquo;s common practice to use a <a href="http://www.virtualenv.org/en/latest/">virtualenv</a> (virtual environment) for your Python projects in order to create self-contained development environments (also called &ldquo;sandboxes&rdquo;). The goal of virtualenv is to prevent different versions of libraries/packages from messing with each other.</p>

<p>Think of virtualenv as a completely isolated container within your computer, where you can utilize any version of Python and install libraries/packages and it won&rsquo;t affect anything outside that container. It&rsquo;s like an isolated, soundproof room within your home where you can scream as loud as you want, about anything you want, and nobody else outside that room can hear it.</p>

<p>Install virtualenv with the following command:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install virtualenv
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Django.1.5"></a>
<h2>Django 1.5</h2>

<p>First released on February 26, 2013, the most notable new features include:</p>

<ol>
<li><em>Configurable User Model</em>: Instead of being forced to use Django&rsquo;s definition of a &ldquo;user&rdquo;, you can now roll your own user model, creating custom fields, like &ndash; links to social profiles, date of birth, favorite color, etc.</li>
<li><em>Python 3 Support</em>: Django suggests not to use Python 3 in production just yet, since support is still &ldquo;experimental&rdquo;. However, this feature is huge for the Python community as a whole, helping to put even more pressure to mirage to the much-improved Python 3.</li>
</ol>


<p>Want to read the full release notes? Check out the official changes from Django <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/releases/1.5/">here</a>.</p>

<p>The latest release came on January 2, 2015: <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.5/releases/1.5.12/">v1.5.12</a></p>

<p><em>Check out the accompanying videos to this tutorial:</em></p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://youtu.be/D0MoGRZRtcA">Setting up a Django Project &ndash; part 1 (setup)</a></li>
<li><a href="http://youtu.be/EuOJRop5aBE">Setting up a Django Project &ndash; part 2 (creating an app)</a></li>
</ul>


<a name="Django.Install"></a>
<h3>Django Install</h3>

<p>Set up your development structure:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>mkdir django15_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>django15_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>virtualenv env
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">source </span>env/bin/activate
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You should see <code>(env)</code> before your prompt, <code>(env)$</code>, indicating that you&rsquo;re running within the &lsquo;env&rsquo; virtualenv.</p>

<p>To exit the virtualenv, type the following command:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>deactivate
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Then reactivate when you&rsquo;re ready to work again.</p>

<p>Let&rsquo;s get Django installed:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install <span class="nv">django</span><span class="o">==</span>1.5.12
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You can check the version by running the following commands:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt; import django
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt; django.get_version<span class="o">()</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="s1">&#39;1.5.12&#39;</span>
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt;
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Project.setup"></a>
<h3>Project setup</h3>

<p><strong>Setup Django project</strong></p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>django-admin.py startproject my_django15_project
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>This creates a new directory called &ldquo;my_django15_project&rdquo; with the basic Django directory and structures:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>├── manage.py
</span><span class='line'>└── my_django15_project
</span><span class='line'>    ├── __init__.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── settings.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── urls.py
</span><span class='line'>    └── wsgi.py
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p><strong>Version control</strong></p>

<p>Before you start any developing, put your project under version control. First, add a new file called <em>.gitignore</em> within your &ldquo;django15_project&rdquo; directory, which is used to ignore unnecessary files from being added to the git repository.</p>

<p>Add the following to the file:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>env
</span><span class='line'>*.DS_Store
</span><span class='line'>*.pyc
</span><span class='line'>__pycache__
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Now initialize (or create) a new Git repo and add your changes to staging and then to the local repo.</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git init
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git add -A
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git commit -am <span class="s2">&quot;initial commit&quot;</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>If you use BitBucket or GitHub (highly recommended), PUSH your files to your central repo.</p>

<a name="Database.settings"></a>
<h3>Database settings</h3>

<p>First, install MySQL-python, which is a database connector for Python:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install MySQL-python
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Edit your <em>settings.py</em> file within your &ldquo;my_django15_project&rdquo; directory to add the following information about your database you setup earlier:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">DATABASES</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s1">&#39;default&#39;</span>: <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;ENGINE&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;django.db.backends.mysql&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;NAME&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;django_db&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;USER&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;root&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;PASSWORD&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;your_password&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="o">}</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">}</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Create your database tables and set up a superuser:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>my_django15_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py syncdb
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Launch the development server:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py runserver
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You should see the following output if Django and the database are setup correctly:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>Validating models...
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>0 errors found
</span><span class='line'>September 7, 2014 - 23:36:02
</span><span class='line'>Django version 1.5, using settings <span class="s1">&#39;my_django15_project.settings&#39;</span>
</span><span class='line'>Development server is running at http://127.0.0.1:8000/
</span><span class='line'>Quit the server with CONTROL-C.
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Point your browser at <a href="http://127.0.0.1:8000">http://127.0.0.1:8000</a> and you should see the Django &ldquo;It worked!&rdquo; page.</p>

<p>Back in your terminal, kill the server by pressing CONTROL-C.</p>

<a name="South"></a>
<h3>South</h3>

<p><a href="http://south.readthedocs.org/en/latest/about.html">South</a> is used for managing changes to your database tables. As your application grows, and you need to add a field to a specific table, for example, you can simply make changes to the database via migrations with South. It makes life <em>much</em> easier.</p>

<p>Install South:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install south
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="pip.freeze"></a>
<h3>pip freeze</h3>

<p>Now that all your libraries are installed, use the following command to create a record of the installed libraries within the &ldquo;my_django15_project&rdquo; directory:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip freeze &gt; requirements.txt
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>This <a href="http://www.pip-installer.org/en/latest/usage.html#pip-freeze">command</a> is incredibly useful if you need to recreate your project from scratch and need to know the exact libraries/versions you need to install.</p>

<p>Commit your new changes to Git.</p>

<a name="Set.up.your.Django.app"></a>
<h3>Set up your Django app</h3>

<p>Create your new app:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py startapp myapp
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Your project structure should now look like this:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>├── manage.py
</span><span class='line'>├── my_django15_project
</span><span class='line'>│   ├── __init__.py
</span><span class='line'>│   ├── settings.py
</span><span class='line'>│   ├── urls.py
</span><span class='line'>│   └── wsgi.py
</span><span class='line'>└── myapp
</span><span class='line'>    ├── __init__.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── models.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── tests.py
</span><span class='line'>    └── views.py
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Update the INSTALLED_APPS in your <em>settings.py</em> file:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='python'><span class='line'><span class="n">INSTALLED_APPS</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.auth&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.contenttypes&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.sessions&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.sites&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.messages&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.staticfiles&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.admin&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;myapp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;south&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="p">)</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Here, we enabled the admin, <code>'django.contrib.admin'</code>, and added the apps, <code>'myapp'</code>, and <code>'south'</code>.</p>

<p>Open <em>urls.py</em> and uncomment these three lines:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='python'><span class='line'><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">django.contrib</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">admin</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="n">admin</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">autodiscover</span><span class="p">()</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="n">url</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">r&#39;^admin/&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">include</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">admin</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">site</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">urls</span><span class="p">)),</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Sync your database again:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py syncdb
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Create a database migration file with South:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py schemamigration myapp --initial
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Migrate the database changes:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py migrate myapp
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Fire up the server (<code>python manage.py runserver</code>), and then navigate to <a href="http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin">http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin</a>. Enter your superuser&rsquo;s username and password to login to the admin page.</p>

<p>Commit to Git. For example:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git add -A
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git commit -am <span class="s2">&quot;updated settings, created app, added south, enabled django admin&quot;</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Using.git..the.right.way"></a>
<h3>Using git, the right way</h3>

<blockquote><p><strong>NOTE</strong>: This section is fairly advanced and completely optional. If this is your first time setting up Django, you can skip this section.</p></blockquote>

<p>If you are not using GitHub or Bitbucket as a central repo, you should create a separate branch of your local repo for development.</p>

<p>First, create a new directory called &ldquo;dev&rdquo; within your &ldquo;django15_project&rdquo; directory, navigate into the newly created directory, and then clone (copy) your entire Django project:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git clone /path/to/your/project/
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<blockquote><p>For example: <code>/Users/michaelherman/desktop/django15_project</code></p></blockquote>

<p>This command creates an exact copy of your repo, which includes all your commits and branches. Always develop from this directory by creating separate branches for each major change to your project:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git branch &lt;branchname&gt;
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Next switch to that branch:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git checkout &lt;branchname&gt;
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You can always check to see what branches are available with this command:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git branch
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>After you are done developing, commit your changes:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git add -A
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git commit -am <span class="s2">&quot;some message&quot;</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Now you want to merge your changes with the master branch:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git checkout master
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git merge &lt;branchname&gt;
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You can PUSH your changes to GitHub or Bitbucket if you use either service. Finally, navigate back to your main production folder and PULL the changes:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git pull
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p><em>Example:</em></p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>dev
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>django15_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git branch 06212013
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git checkout 06212013
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git add -A
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git commit -am <span class="s2">&quot;description of changes made&quot;</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git checkout master
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git merge 06212013
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd</span> ..
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">(</span>env<span class="o">)</span><span class="nv">$ </span>git pull /Users/michaelherman/desktop/django15_project/dev/django15_project
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Workflow"></a>
<h3>Workflow</h3>

<p>Now that your app is set up, follow either of these simple workflows every time you want to make changes to your app:</p>

<p><strong>Basic:</strong></p>

<ol>
<li>Navigate to your project</li>
<li>Activate virtualenv</li>
<li>Develop</li>
<li>Commit changes</li>
<li>Deploy</li>
<li>Deactivate virtualenv</li>
</ol>


<p><strong>Advanced:</strong></p>

<ol>
<li>Navigate to your project</li>
<li>Activate virtualenv</li>
<li>Create and checkout a new git branch</li>
<li>Develop</li>
<li>Commit changes</li>
<li>Merge the new branch with your master branch</li>
<li>PULL the changes into the production folder</li>
<li>Deploy</li>
<li>Deactivate virtualenv</li>
</ol>


<p>Cheers! Any questions? Suggestions?</p>

<p>Let&rsquo;s create a basic <a href="https://realpython.com/learn/start-django/#create-an-app">app</a>!</p>

<a name="Django.1.6"></a>
<h2>Django 1.6</h2>

<p>First released on November 6, 2013, the most notable new features include:</p>

<ol>
<li><em>Python 3 Support</em>: Support for Python 3 is now official, without any restrictions so you can run it in production.</li>
<li><em>Improved Database Transaction Management</em>: The API is leaner, cleaner, and simpler, making rollbacks and error handling much easier.</li>
<li><em>New Test Runner</em></li>
<li><em>Persistent Database Connections</em></li>
</ol>


<p>Want to read the full release notes? Check out the official changes from Django <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/releases/1.6/">here</a>.</p>

<p>The latest release came on March 18, 2015: <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.6/releases/1.6.11/">v1.6.11</a></p>

<a name="Django.Install"></a>
<h3>Django Install</h3>

<p>Set up your development structure:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>mkdir django16_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>django16_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>virtualenv env
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">source </span>env/bin/activate
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You should see <code>(env)</code> before your prompt, <code>(env)$</code>, indicating that you&rsquo;re running within the &lsquo;env&rsquo; virtualenv.</p>

<p>To exit the virtualenv, type the following command:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>deactivate
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Then reactivate when you&rsquo;re ready to work again.</p>

<p>With your virtualenv activated, install with Pip:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install <span class="nv">django</span><span class="o">==</span>1.6.11
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You can check the version by running the following commands:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt; import django
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt; django.get_version<span class="o">()</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="s1">&#39;1.6.11&#39;</span>
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt;
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="Project.setup"></a>
<h3>Project setup</h3>

<p><strong>Setup Django project</strong></p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>django-admin.py startproject my_django16_project
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>This creates a new directory called &ldquo;my_django16_project&rdquo; with the basic Django directory and structures:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>├── manage.py
</span><span class='line'>└── my_django16_project
</span><span class='line'>    ├── __init__.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── settings.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── urls.py
</span><span class='line'>    └── wsgi.py
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p><strong>Version control</strong></p>

<p>Before you start any developing, place your project under version control. First, add a <em>.gitignore</em> file within your &ldquo;django16_project&rdquo; directory, which prevent unnecessary files from being added to the git repository.</p>

<p>Add the following to the file:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>env
</span><span class='line'>*.DS_Store
</span><span class='line'>*.pyc
</span><span class='line'>__pycache__
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Now initialize (or create) a new Git repo and add your changes to staging and then to the repo.</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git init
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git add -A
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git commit -am <span class="s2">&quot;initial&quot;</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>If you use GitHub, PUSH your files to your central repo as well.</p>

<a name="Database.settings"></a>
<h3>Database settings</h3>

<p>First, install MySQL-python so that Python can communicate with MySQL:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install MySQL-python
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Edit your <em>settings.py</em> file within your &ldquo;my_django16_project&rdquo; directory:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">DATABASES</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s1">&#39;default&#39;</span>: <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;ENGINE&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;django.db.backends.mysql&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;NAME&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;django_db&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;USER&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;root&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="s1">&#39;PASSWORD&#39;</span>: <span class="s1">&#39;your_password&#39;</span>,
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="o">}</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">}</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Create your database tables and set up a superuser:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>my
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py syncdb
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Launch the development server:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>my_django16_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py runserver
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You should see the following output if all is well thus far:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>Validating models...
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>0 errors found
</span><span class='line'>September 7, 2014 - 23:36:02
</span><span class='line'>Django version 1.6, using settings <span class="s1">&#39;my_django16_project.settings&#39;</span>
</span><span class='line'>Development server is running at http://127.0.0.1:8000/
</span><span class='line'>Quit the server with CONTROL-C.
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Navigate to <a href="http://127.0.0.1:8000">http://127.0.0.1:8000</a> and you should see the familiar light-blue &ldquo;It worked!&rdquo; page.</p>

<p>Kill the server by pressing CONTROL-C back in the terminal.</p>

<a name="South"></a>
<h3>South</h3>

<p><a href="http://south.readthedocs.org/en/latest/about.html">South</a> is used for handling database migrations &ndash; e.g, making changes to your database schema.</p>

<p>Install South:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install south
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<a name="pip.freeze"></a>
<h3>pip freeze</h3>

<p>With the dependencies installed, use the following command to create a record of them, along with their subsequent versions, within the &ldquo;my_django16_project&rdquo; directory:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip freeze &gt; requirements.txt
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>This <a href="http://www.pip-installer.org/en/latest/usage.html#pip-freeze">command</a> comes in handy when you need to recreate your project from scratch. You can simply run <code>pip install -r requirements.txt</code> to install all your project&rsquo;s dependencies.</p>

<p>Commit your new changes to Git.</p>

<a name="Set.up.your.Django.app"></a>
<h3>Set up your Django app</h3>

<p>Create your new app:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py startapp myapp
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Your project structure should now look like this:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
<span class='line-number'>12</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>├── manage.py
</span><span class='line'>├── my_django16_project
</span><span class='line'>│   ├── __init__.py
</span><span class='line'>│   ├── settings.py
</span><span class='line'>│   ├── urls.py
</span><span class='line'>│   └── wsgi.py
</span><span class='line'>└── myapp
</span><span class='line'>    ├── __init__.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── admin.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── models.py
</span><span class='line'>    ├── tests.py
</span><span class='line'>    └── views.py
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Update the INSTALLED_APPS in your <em>settings.py</em> file to include South as well as your new app:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='python'><span class='line'><span class="n">INSTALLED_APPS</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.auth&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.contenttypes&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.sessions&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.sites&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.messages&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.staticfiles&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;django.contrib.admin&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;myapp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="s">&#39;south&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="p">)</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Now as soon as you run <code>syncdb</code>, Django will be aware of both <code>south</code> and <code>myapp</code>.</p>

<p>Open <em>urls.py</em> and uncomment these three lines:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='python'><span class='line'><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">django.contrib</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">admin</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="n">admin</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">autodiscover</span><span class="p">()</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="n">url</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">r&#39;^admin/&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">include</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">admin</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">site</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">urls</span><span class="p">)),</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Sync your database again:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py syncdb
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Create a database migration file with South:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py schemamigration myapp --initial
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Migrate the database changes:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python manage.py migrate myapp
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Fire up the server (<code>python manage.py runserver</code>), and then navigate to <a href="http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin">http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin</a>. Enter your superuser&rsquo;s username and password to login to the admin page. This is just a sanity check to ensure that all is working.</p>

<p>Commit to Git. For example:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git add -A
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>git commit -am <span class="s2">&quot;updated settings, created app, added south, enabled django admin, boom&quot;</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>All set. Let&rsquo;s create a basic <a href="https://realpython.com/learn/start-django/#create-an-app">app</a>!</p>

<a name="Django.1.7"></a>
<h2>Django 1.7</h2>

<p>First released on September 2, 2014, the most notable new features include:</p>

<ol>
<li><em>Database Migrations</em>: Django now has built-in support for making database schema changes, which is based on South. This is big!</li>
<li><em>Improved <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.7/ref/checks/">system</a> checking tools for validating and checking your projects</em></li>
<li><em>Refactoring of how Django identifies and loads applications</em></li>
</ol>


<p>Want to read the full release notes? Check out the official changes from Django <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/releases/1.7/">here</a>.</p>

<p>The latest release came on May 1, 2015: <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.7/releases/1.7.8/">v1.7.8</a></p>

<a name="Django.Install"></a>
<h3>Django Install</h3>

<p>Set up a development structure:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>mkdir django17_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>django17_project
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>virtualenv env
</span><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">source </span>env/bin/activate
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You should see <code>(env)</code> before your prompt, <code>(env)$</code>, indicating that your virtualenv is activated.</p>

<p>To deactivate the virtualenv:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>deactivate
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>Then reactivate once you&rsquo;re ready to start developing again.</p>

<p>With your virtualenv activated, install Django with Pip:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>pip install <span class="nv">django</span><span class="o">==</span>1.7.8
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You can check the version by running the following commands:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>python
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt; import django
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt; django.get_version<span class="o">()</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="s1">&#39;1.7.8&#39;</span>
</span><span class='line'>&gt;&gt;&gt;
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


